you think I dropped the ball?

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:27.550
By a show of hands, who
does not really care?

00:13:27.550 --> 00:13:28.850
[Laughter].

00:13:28.850 --> 00:13:32.100
Okay because none of, a lot of
you did not raise your hands.

00:13:32.100 --> 00:13:36.580
I dropped the touchdown pass
in my hands in the end zone.

00:13:36.580 --> 00:13:37.880
Homecoming game.

00:13:37.880 --> 00:13:39.390
All my friends were there.

00:13:39.390 --> 00:13:40.860
My family was there.

00:13:40.860 --> 00:13:42.980
I felt like I was about this big.

00:13:42.980 --> 00:13:44.280
Walked to the sideline.

00:13:44.280 --> 00:13:47.160
My coach, Jimmy Green,
grabbed me by the facemask.

00:13:47.160 --> 00:13:50.090
I was waiting to be like
ejected onto the bench.

00:13:50.090 --> 00:13:51.990 position:56%
And he said to me, I believe in you.

00:13:51.990 --> 00:13:55.550
Go back out there and catch the
ball this time, okay [laughter].

00:13:55.550 --> 00:13:58.570
So I am running down the
sideline the second time.

00:13:58.570 --> 00:13:59.870
I am running.

00:13:59.870 --> 00:14:01.170
I am running.

00:14:01.170 --> 00:14:02.470
The ball is coming.

00:14:02.470 --> 00:14:03.770
The crowd is screaming.

00:14:03.770 --> 00:14:05.070
I am running and running and
running and running and running.

00:14:05.070 --> 00:14:06.870
I could read Spaulding
on the side of the ball.

00:14:06.870 --> 00:14:08.630
I was so laser beam focused.

00:14:08.630 --> 00:14:11.550
I caught the ball.

00:14:11.550 --> 00:14:14.670
Unbeknownst to me, there was a
college scout from the University

00:14:14.670 --> 00:14:15.970
of Richmond who was looking to see

00:14:15.970 --> 00:14:17.770
if I could play football
at Richmond.

00:14:17.770 --> 00:14:22.700
He walked out of the
stadium on the first drop.

00:14:22.700 --> 00:14:27.580
He heard the crowd screaming
the second time and he came back

00:14:27.580 --> 00:14:31.600
in the stadium and he looked over
and he saw me in the end zone

00:14:31.600 --> 00:14:32.960
like you know [laughter].

00:14:32.960 --> 00:14:39.440
That one catch resulted in a
180 thousand dollar scholarship

00:14:39.440 --> 00:14:41.710
to the University of
Richmond [applause].

00:14:41.710 --> 00:14:44.010
And the reason.

00:14:45.100 --> 00:14:46.660
I think I can, right?

00:14:46.660 --> 00:14:51.020
The reason he gave me
that opportunity is

00:14:51.020 --> 00:14:53.870 position:56%
because he said you did not give up.

00:14:53.870 --> 00:14:55.640
The grit. The perseverance.

00:14:55.640 --> 00:14:56.940
The grace.

00:14:56.940 --> 00:15:00.550 position:56%
All those things that I have talked
about in the book, he believed in me

00:15:00.550 --> 00:15:02.250
because I did not give up.

00:15:02.250 --> 00:15:05.070
And that is the message
that I have tried to put

00:15:05.070 --> 00:15:09.630
to weave throughout the book is
that opportunities come to you,

00:15:09.630 --> 00:15:12.170
but you have to be prepared
for that opportunity.

00:15:12.170 --> 00:15:14.390
And having that one
person in your life.

00:15:14.390 --> 00:15:18.080
All you need is one that has
your back and believes in you.

00:15:18.080 --> 00:15:20.110
And I had many of those people.

00:15:20.110 --> 00:15:21.630
But he was one of them.

00:15:21.630 --> 00:15:24.470
Went to Richmond, football
scholarship, majored in chemistry.

00:15:24.470 --> 00:15:29.330
Was still blowing things up, but
now I could legally do it you know

00:15:29.330 --> 00:15:31.720
and not get a spanking
from my mother.

00:15:31.720 --> 00:15:34.500
Played football there O
and 10, three and eight.

00:15:34.500 --> 00:15:37.470
We did not do too well my
freshman year or my sophomore year.

00:15:37.470 --> 00:15:39.510
But we ended up going to
the play offs my junior

00:15:39.510 --> 00:15:41.090
and senior year because we kept on.

00:15:41.090 --> 00:15:42.390
We did not give up.

00:15:42.390 --> 00:15:44.630
And then I got drafted
to the Detroit Lions.

00:15:44.630 --> 00:15:47.440
Detroit, yeah Robin, yeah.

00:15:47.440 --> 00:15:49.320
Detroit Lions in the 11th round.

00:15:49.320 --> 00:15:52.250
Pulled a hamstring
muscle in training camp.

00:15:52.250 --> 00:15:55.180
And then I came back
home and my agent said,

00:15:55.180 --> 00:15:57.820
Dallas wants to sign
you for the next season.

00:15:57.820 --> 00:16:04.750
So I have from August of 1986
until maybe March of 1987 to figure

00:16:04.750 --> 00:16:07.510
out what I am going to do with
my life for those few months.

00:16:07.510 --> 00:16:10.760 position:56%
And this professor at the
University of Virginia said come up,

00:16:10.760 --> 00:16:13.170
I want to talk to you about
being a research assistant here.

00:16:13.170 --> 00:16:16.550
I am like, but I am going
to play football, man.

00:16:16.550 --> 00:16:17.970
You know. Research assistant

00:16:17.970 --> 00:16:20.550
and football do not
really you know match.

00:16:20.550 --> 00:16:21.850
I go up there.

00:16:21.850 --> 00:16:24.130
I start working for him
as a research assistant.

00:16:24.130 --> 00:16:26.580
And then when the January
semester started

00:16:26.580 --> 00:16:28.730
for material science engineering,

00:16:28.730 --> 00:16:32.050
I enrolled knowing I would
be leaving in three months.

00:16:32.050 --> 00:16:36.450
And I went to UVA,
started the program.

00:16:36.450 --> 00:16:38.850
And then they videotaped
the courses, VHS [laughter].

00:16:38.850 --> 00:16:43.200
Old school, right.

00:16:43.200 --> 00:16:46.690
So by day I am catching
footballs for America's team.

00:16:46.690 --> 00:16:50.190
I mean they cut me too so I do not.

00:16:50.190 --> 00:16:53.040
You know, we are in
[inaudible] territory right.

00:16:53.040 --> 00:16:55.430
But. And I was playing football

00:16:55.430 --> 00:16:56.920
and watching material
science engineering.

00:16:56.920 --> 00:16:58.850
And when I pulled my
hamstring for the second time,

00:16:58.850 --> 00:17:00.150
it was the end of my
football career.

00:17:00.150 --> 00:17:02.790
That is when I went right back
and finished my master's degree

00:17:02.790 --> 00:17:05.090
at the University of Virginia.

00:17:05.090 --> 00:17:07.810 position:56%
And so that was my foray in the NFL.

00:17:07.810 --> 00:17:10.970
This was the last catch
in a preseason game.

00:17:10.970 --> 00:17:15.540
But I had that second
chance for my academics.

00:17:15.540 --> 00:17:20.960 position:56%
And NASA Langley Research Center, I
worked there as a research scientist

00:17:20.960 --> 00:17:23.250
with my friend, Rudy King, here.

00:17:23.250 --> 00:17:26.580
And we were developing
sensors to help

00:17:26.580 --> 00:17:28.880
with the space shuttle
and the space program.

00:17:28.880 --> 00:17:32.350
And a friend of mine said, Leland
you would be a great astronaut.

00:17:32.350 --> 00:17:35.830
And I am like, yeah right.

00:17:35.830 --> 00:17:38.230
He saw something I
did not see in myself.

00:17:38.230 --> 00:17:39.920
And he handed me an application.

00:17:39.920 --> 00:17:41.220
I looked at it.

00:17:41.220 --> 00:17:42.520
I did not fill out.

00:17:42.520 --> 00:17:46.390
But another friend of mine filled
the application out and he got in.

00:17:46.390 --> 00:17:50.280
And I said to myself, if NASA is
letting knuckleheads like that

00:17:50.280 --> 00:17:53.950
in to be astronauts,
maybe I can be one too.

00:17:53.950 --> 00:17:59.040
So I applied in the next selection,
which was 1987 for the 1988 class.

00:17:59.040 --> 00:18:00.460
And I got in.

00:18:00.460 --> 00:18:06.040 position:56%
And I think about all the people
that have been in the space program.

00:18:06.040 --> 00:18:07.340
362 people.

00:18:07.340 --> 00:18:09.670
I am in there somewhere.

00:18:09.670 --> 00:18:11.170
I had this opportunity.

00:18:11.170 --> 00:18:16.210
This small kid from Lynchburg,
Virginia being one of 362 Americans

00:18:16.210 --> 00:18:19.600
to have an opportunity
to fly in space.

00:18:19.600 --> 00:18:25.780 position:56%
Now, our class was 25 U.S. out of
25 hundred people, 25 were selected.

00:18:25.780 --> 00:18:28.870
And we had six international
astronauts.

00:18:28.870 --> 00:18:32.050
Now, can you guys find me
in the picture anywhere?

00:18:32.050 --> 00:18:35.610
[Laughter].

00:18:35.610 --> 00:18:38.330
In the front row.

00:18:38.330 --> 00:18:40.290
On the side.

00:18:40.290 --> 00:18:42.790
Let me give you a little
hand there [laughter].

00:18:42.790 --> 00:18:44.170
There is Leland in there.

00:18:44.170 --> 00:18:47.970
A very diverse group of people.

00:18:47.970 --> 00:18:50.160
Navy, Air Force, Marines.

00:18:50.160 --> 00:18:55.120
It was an incredible class
of people working together

00:18:55.120 --> 00:18:57.540
to help advance our civilization.

00:18:57.540 --> 00:19:00.460
And I was in Russia for two
years working with the first crew

00:19:00.460 --> 00:19:02.780
that was going to the
International Space Station.

00:19:02.780 --> 00:19:05.440
Bill Shepherd, Yuri
Gidzenko and Sergei Krikalev.

00:19:05.440 --> 00:19:06.920
And we did all this training.

00:19:06.920 --> 00:19:09.680
And I was doing pushups
in the zero G airplane,

00:19:09.680 --> 00:19:12.960
which is affectionately
known as the vomit comet.

00:19:12.960 --> 00:19:14.430
But we were doing all these things

00:19:14.430 --> 00:19:16.620
to get these guys ready
to fly in space.

00:19:16.620 --> 00:19:17.960
Expedition one.

00:19:17.960 --> 00:19:19.550 position:56%
The first crew to the Space Station.

00:19:19.550 --> 00:19:25.080
And when I came home, it was
time for me to do more training.

00:19:25.080 --> 00:19:26.830
This is the Neutral
Buoyancy Laboratory.

00:19:26.830 --> 00:19:29.190
It is a six million gallon pool

00:19:29.190 --> 00:19:32.980
that we have a submerged space
station and space shuttle.

00:19:32.980 --> 00:19:37.770
We go about 30 feet deep in
this pool to do this training.

00:19:37.770 --> 00:19:42.290
And you do it in this white
Michelin man looking suit.

00:19:42.290 --> 00:19:46.810
There is one little piece of
hardware that goes in the suit

00:19:46.810 --> 00:19:52.120
that can be very critical to
your success in the water.

00:19:52.120 --> 00:19:55.220
There is a pad called
a Valsalva pad.

00:19:55.220 --> 00:19:58.200
It is a Styrofoam block that
you press your nose against.

00:19:58.200 --> 00:19:59.580
That if you are the kind
of person that needs

00:19:59.580 --> 00:20:01.660
to squeeze your nose to clear.

00:20:01.660 --> 00:20:04.020
That allows you to press
your nose against it

00:20:04.020 --> 00:20:06.990
in the helmet to clear your ears.

00:20:06.990 --> 00:20:10.870
I am the kind of person that
needs to squeeze to clear.

00:20:10.870 --> 00:20:14.010
They forgot to put mine in.

00:20:14.010 --> 00:20:17.140
We go down about 20 feet
and I tell the test director

00:20:17.140 --> 00:20:19.360
to turn the volume
in the headset up.

00:20:19.360 --> 00:20:22.580
I hear nothing from
static from that point on.

00:20:22.580 --> 00:20:24.270
They are taking me up and down

00:20:24.270 --> 00:20:26.200
in the pool trying to
get my ears to clear.

00:20:26.200 --> 00:20:29.620
And I do not hear anything.

00:20:29.620 --> 00:20:33.920
Let's back up four days
before this thing happened.

00:20:33.920 --> 00:20:35.930
My parents were having their
35th wedding anniversary

00:20:35.930 --> 00:20:37.230
in Lynchburg, Virginia.

00:20:37.230 --> 00:20:39.030
Not far from Pierce Street.

00:20:39.030 --> 00:20:40.450
My cousin was in the car with me.

00:20:40.450 --> 00:20:42.980
I was dropping them off at a hotel.

00:20:42.980 --> 00:20:44.640
And she had her friend
with her named Janette.

00:20:44.640 --> 00:20:50.120
Janette said to me, something
is going to happen to you.

00:20:50.120 --> 00:20:53.220
No one is going to
know why this happened.

00:20:53.220 --> 00:20:54.810
You will be healed of this.

00:20:54.810 --> 00:20:57.010
You will fly in space.

00:20:57.010 --> 00:20:59.400
This will be your testimony
you share with the world.

00:20:59.400 --> 00:21:04.720
And I am like, um [laughter], okay.

00:21:04.720 --> 00:21:08.590
I had just come back from
Russia with the first crew.

00:21:08.590 --> 00:21:10.210
The next four days later I am going

00:21:10.210 --> 00:21:14.390
to start my training
to be a space walker.

00:21:14.390 --> 00:21:16.410
And the first people
to get their training

00:21:16.410 --> 00:21:19.350
to be space walkers were building
an international space station.

00:21:19.350 --> 00:21:22.100
You need space walkers to do that.

00:21:22.100 --> 00:21:26.950
She is telling me something
is going to happen to me.

00:21:26.950 --> 00:21:28.690
And I listen to people, you know.

00:21:28.690 --> 00:21:31.140
I did not shut her down.

00:21:31.140 --> 00:21:35.060
Four days later, I
am completely deaf.

00:21:35.060 --> 00:21:36.360
They take me out of the pool.

00:21:36.360 --> 00:21:37.920
They take my helmet off.

00:21:37.920 --> 00:21:41.200
The flight surgeon walks over
to me and he is talking to me.

00:21:41.200 --> 00:21:45.190
I think he is joking with me
because he is moving his lips

00:21:45.190 --> 00:21:46.490
and I do not hear anything.

00:21:46.490 --> 00:21:48.260
He touches my right ear.

00:21:48.260 --> 00:21:51.000
He pulls his finger back and
I feel the blood streaming

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:54.120
down the side of my face.

00:21:54.120 --> 00:21:56.850
They rush me to the hospital.

00:21:56.850 --> 00:21:59.640
And these are the faces
of my surgeons [laughter].

00:21:59.640 --> 00:22:05.820 position:56%
Does not look to optimistic does it?

00:22:05.820 --> 00:22:07.260
They went in and operated.

00:22:07.260 --> 00:22:08.770
They went in to look around to see

00:22:08.770 --> 00:22:12.280
if I had something called a
purulent fistula where the,

00:22:12.280 --> 00:22:14.860
I was leaking out of my
ears, on the inner ear,

00:22:14.860 --> 00:22:18.180
the oval and circular windows.

00:22:18.180 --> 00:22:19.480
And they could not find anything.

00:22:19.480 --> 00:22:21.570
Everything was intact.

00:22:21.570 --> 00:22:25.650
And about three weeks later,
my hearing slowly came back.

00:22:25.650 --> 00:22:30.560
I am still impaired in my left ear,
probably 90 percent of it is gone.

00:22:30.560 --> 00:22:33.390
So as an astronaut hearing
is kind of important, right?

00:22:33.390 --> 00:22:39.370
And they immediately medically
disqualify me to fly in space.

00:22:39.370 --> 00:22:41.810
They said you are never
going to fly in space.

00:22:41.810 --> 00:22:43.830
My doctors told me that.

00:22:43.830 --> 00:22:46.050
And I was trying to conjure up all
these things, the Little Engine

00:22:46.050 --> 00:22:47.580
That Could, I think
I can, I think I can.

00:22:47.580 --> 00:22:48.880
Curious George.

00:22:48.880 --> 00:22:50.810
All these things.

00:22:50.810 --> 00:22:53.310
And when I opened my laptop
up and watched a movie,

00:22:53.310 --> 00:22:59.210
I realized when I could not
hear the sound that I was deaf.

00:22:59.210 --> 00:23:00.780
My friends consoled me.

00:23:00.780 --> 00:23:02.830
The people who looked out for me.

00:23:02.830 --> 00:23:06.100
But I was still deaf
in this hospital room.

00:23:06.100 --> 00:23:11.060
The head of all of NASA, Daniel
Goldin, came to visit me.

00:23:11.060 --> 00:23:16.810
And these legal pads are my way
of communicating with the world.

00:23:16.810 --> 00:23:19.660
I could talk, but I would have

00:23:19.660 --> 00:23:22.720
to hear what they say
through this writing.

00:23:22.720 --> 00:23:24.370
He said I am not going to give
up on you like we did not give

00:23:24.370 --> 00:23:26.190
up on the Hubble Space Telescope.

00:23:26.190 --> 00:23:29.730
It needed corrective
vision when it was launched.

00:23:29.730 --> 00:23:33.370
And he wrote me this long letter

00:23:33.370 --> 00:23:38.170
about the Hubble's first image it
took was this eagle's nest nebula

00:23:38.170 --> 00:23:41.640
seven thousand light years from
Earth, one light year in length,

00:23:41.640 --> 00:23:43.930
the place where stars are born.

00:23:43.930 --> 00:23:46.050
He gave me his cell phone number.

00:23:46.050 --> 00:23:50.180
He said I will never give up on
you, I will never give up on you.

00:23:50.180 --> 00:23:52.760
And then three months
later he was fired

00:23:52.760 --> 00:23:55.660
and I am like, oh man [laughter].

00:23:55.660 --> 00:23:59.190
That cell phone is no
longer any good, you know.

00:23:59.190 --> 00:24:02.480
But you know my hearing did come
back and they were trying to figure

00:24:02.480 --> 00:24:06.010
out what to do with me as a you
know hearing impaired astronaut.

00:24:06.010 --> 00:24:08.680
So I came up to Washington
D.C. to work in education.

00:24:08.680 --> 00:24:10.340
And we started this program

00:24:10.340 --> 00:24:13.000
in 2003 called the
Educator Astronaut Program,

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:14.720
where we were going to hire,

00:24:14.720 --> 00:24:18.080
let students nominate their
teachers to become astronauts.

00:24:18.080 --> 00:24:22.050
And we actually hired three
teachers that have flown in space.

00:24:22.050 --> 00:24:24.550
And done space walks and
done all these things.

00:24:24.550 --> 00:24:28.110
But I was not going to fly because
I was medically disqualified.

00:24:28.110 --> 00:24:31.050
And around that same
time, February 1st, 2003,

00:24:31.050 --> 00:24:32.840
we lost Space Shuttle Columbia.

00:24:32.840 --> 00:24:35.640
Many of you remember this.

00:24:35.640 --> 00:24:41.080 position:56%
And you know exactly where you were
when it broke up over the Texas sky.

00:24:41.080 --> 00:24:45.070
I went to David Brown, who is the
gentleman in the top left corner.

00:24:45.070 --> 00:24:47.180
He was a military test pilot.

00:24:47.180 --> 00:24:48.480
He was a medical doctor.

00:24:48.480 --> 00:24:52.000
He was the doctor that was
actually doing the investigation

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:55.010
on me for my hearing.

00:24:55.010 --> 00:24:57.040
And he perished.

00:24:57.040 --> 00:25:02.860
We were going to have, do a photo
shoot when he got back home.

00:25:02.860 --> 00:25:04.760
He never made it back.

00:25:04.760 --> 00:25:08.500
In the bottom left corner,
that is David's father

00:25:08.500 --> 00:25:10.770
at Arlington National Cemetery.

00:25:10.770 --> 00:25:15.390
We went around the country to
the different memorial services.

00:25:15.390 --> 00:25:19.030
We are flying in the NASA
jet, taking off and landing.

00:25:19.030 --> 00:25:22.780
And the chief of all the flight
surgeons is sitting beside me

00:25:22.780 --> 00:25:26.630
on every mission, on every
launch and landing, taking notes.

00:25:26.630 --> 00:25:31.430
When we finished the last memorial
service, he called me in his office

00:25:31.430 --> 00:25:34.440
and he said, Leland
I believe in you.

00:25:34.440 --> 00:25:37.670
Here is a waiver for
you to fly in space.

00:25:37.670 --> 00:25:43.350
When I think about this journey
so far, my friends who came

00:25:43.350 --> 00:25:47.950
into that hospital room wrote me
notes saying, you should sue NASA,

00:25:47.950 --> 00:25:51.300
write a book and get
paid [laughter].

00:25:51.300 --> 00:25:52.600
They hurt you.

00:25:52.600 --> 00:25:54.910
And they told you, you are
never going to fly in space.

00:25:54.910 --> 00:25:58.230
I believed that that
was not the way to go.

00:25:58.230 --> 00:26:02.000
I believe that there is more to
this journey and to not give up

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:05.250
and to have that grit
and perseverance.

00:26:05.250 --> 00:26:07.220
And I signed.

00:26:07.220 --> 00:26:09.210
I got that waiver.

00:26:09.210 --> 00:26:12.730
I went home to Houston
and said look what I got.

00:26:12.730 --> 00:26:14.980
And this was the picture I took

00:26:14.980 --> 00:26:18.160
when I first got assigned
to my first flight.

